    "recap_headline": "United States Air Force Academy",
    "recap_text": "U.S. AIR FORCE ACADEMY, Colo., -\nAir Force baseball (7-11) bested St. Thomas (4-15), 20-12, on Monday afternoon at Erdle Field. The Falcon hitters combined for 14 hits, 17 RBIs, five doubles, and a pair of homers. The pitchers posted eight strikeouts.\nAt the plate,\nT.J. Oster\nand\nTripp Garrish\nboth batted three runs in, while\nBen Niednagel\n,\nWalker Zapp\n,\nWyatt Hanoian\n, and\nLuke Elmore\nrecorded one apiece.\nFreshman\nAiden Poe\n(2-0) earned his second career win after matching his career-high 4.1 innings. He struck out three batters and allowed four runs.\nTrey Rutledge\ngave up a trio of runs while logging two strikeouts in 0.2 innings, while\nDavis Rhyne\nentered for one inning and allowed one earned run.\nEthan Dillinger\nand\nEaston Miller\nclosed the last two frames.\nAfter a scoreless first inning, the Falcons put a pair of runs on the board in the second after Hanoian drew a walk and was brought home on a Garrish homer.\nThe Tommies took over at 3-2 in the top of the third.\nTheir lead did not last long, as Air Force kept their momentum going with a trio of their own runs in the bottom of the same frame, 5-2.\nKayden Bradshaw\nopened the inning with a double to left, stole third, and scored on a single from Niednagel. On two fielder's choices, Zapp and Garrish reached base. Both were able to score on a failed pickoff attempt by St. Thomas' catcher.\nIn the bottom of the fourth, the Falcons put up a seven-spot, extending into a 12-3 advantage. Oster singled and stole second to begin the frame and was joined on base by a walked\nBrooks Burdine\n. The pair pulled off a double steal before Bradshaw was hit by a pitch. With bases loaded, Niednagel singled to plate Oster, but Burdine was thrown out on the play trying to head home. A double from Zapp sent one run across the plate and put Niednagel on third. All the runners took advantage of a wild pitch and Garrish was issued a walk to reload the bases. Elmore received credit for an RBI after being hit by a pitch and Oster cleared the bags with a double to right field.\nSt. Thomas tacked on four runs but still trailed 12-7 in the top of the fifth inning.\nAir Force continued to pull ahead in the bottom of five, adding a pair of runs, 14-7. With one out, Bradshaw flew through the bases for an inside-the-park home run after sending the ball deep into left center. Zapp reached on another fielder's choice and scored from first on a Hanoian double.\nIn the top of the sixth, the Tommies recorded their final runs of the day but were behind 14-11.\nThe Falcons maintained offensive power, scoring five runs in the sixth, 19-11. To open the inning,\nVan Klein\nsingled, Burdine walked, and Bradshaw executed a bunt single to fill the bags.\nDawson Thrush\nwas credited with an RBI after being hit by a pitch, while Zapp and Hanoian walked in runs. Following a pitching change for the Tommies, Garrish and Elmore both logged RBI fielder's choices.\nThe top of the seventh saw AF plate their 20\nth\nrun of the game, 20-11 when Burdine scored on a single from pinch hitter\nBrooks Ward\n.\\\nSt. Thomas scored one more run for good measure in the top of eight for a final score of 20-12.\nAir Force will travel to Reno for their second Mountain West series of the season on Friday March 20-Sunday March 22 against Nevada."
  },
